INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6add8d6f-a3a0-4cbd-adf8-d56402966e6a',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Java's JIT Compiler — Why Your App Gets Faster While Running$escape$,
  $escape$Java doesn't compile straight to native machine code, nor does it purely interpret bytecode at runtime. The JVM uses a tiered execution model. Initially, the interpreter runs your `.class` bytecode directly — fast startup, but slow throughput. As the JVM profiles hot methods (tracked via invocation counters), the C1 compiler kicks in at Tier 3 with lightweight optimizations. Sustained hotness triggers C2 (the server compiler) at Tier 4, applying aggressive JIT techniques: inlining, escape analysis, loop unrolling, and devirtualization.

This is why Java apps suffer cold starts — the JVM hasn't gathered enough profile data to optimize yet. GraalVM Native Image sidesteps this entirely by performing ahead-of-time (AOT) compilation at build time, producing a native binary with no JVM warmup. The tradeoff: no runtime profiling means less adaptive optimization.

For Spring Boot microservices, cold start is a real problem in serverless/container environments. Options: GraalVM Native (`spring-boot:build-image` with `native` profile), CRaC (Checkpoint/Restore), or `-XX:TieredStopAtLevel=1` to skip C2 and favor startup over peak throughput.$escape$,
  $escape$// Check JIT compilation activity at runtime
import java.lang.management.ManagementFactory;
import com.sun.management.HotSpotDiagnosticMXBean;

public class JitInspector {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        var compiler = ManagementFactory.getCompilationMXBean();
        System.out.println("JIT Compiler: " + compiler.getName());
        System.out.println("Total compile time (ms): " + compiler.getTotalCompilationTime());

        // Run with: -XX:+PrintCompilation to see methods being JIT-compiled
        // Run with: -XX:+UnlockDiagnosticVMOptions -XX:+PrintInlining for inlining decisions
        // GraalVM AOT: mvn -Pnative spring-boot:build-image
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$java$escape$,
