INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6ed71a93-492c-4cbc-8123-e55624b6f603',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Java Dev Tooling — JShell, JPDA Debugging, and jdtls for LSP-Powered Editors$escape$,
  $escape$Java 9+ ships JShell, a full REPL that loads your classpath on startup — ideal for prototyping streams, testing regex, or verifying library behavior without a full compile cycle. Launch it with `jshell --class-path build/libs/myapp.jar` and iterate instantly.

For debugging, Java uses JPDA (Java Platform Debugger Architecture). Remote debugging over JDWP is the standard approach: start your JVM with `-agentlib:jdwp=transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=*:5005`, then attach any JPDA-compliant client — jdb, IntelliJ, or VS Code. Conditional breakpoints and hot-swap via HCR (Hot Code Replace) work within the same method body without restarting.

Editor LSP support runs through Eclipse JDT Language Server (`jdtls`). It provides full semantic analysis, inlay hints, auto-imports, and `textDocument/codeAction` for refactors. Neovim users wire it via `nvim-jdtls` with per-project `workspace` isolation. VS Code uses the same jdtls binary under the hood via the Java Extension Pack. Key config: point `java.home` at a JDK 17+ installation — jdtls itself requires it even if your project targets an older release.$escape$,
  $escape$# Start JShell with a fat JAR on the classpath
jshell --class-path build/libs/myapp-all.jar

# Inside JShell — test a stream pipeline immediately
jshell> import java.util.List;
jshell> List.of("alpha", "beta", "gamma")
...>     .stream()
...>     .filter(s -> s.startsWith("a"))
...>     .map(String::toUpperCase)
...>     .toList()
$1 ==> [ALPHA]

# Launch JVM with JDWP for remote debugging (suspend=n = don't wait for client)
java -agentlib:jdwp=transport=dt_socket,server=y,suspend=n,address=*:5005 -jar myapp.jar$escape$,
  $escape$bash$escape$,
