INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'c1dd3c87-db7a-4a91-b77b-94c1692bc563',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Java's Thread-Per-Request Model and Why It Limits Horizontal Scaling$escape$,
  $escape$Java's traditional thread-per-request model (Servlet API, Spring MVC) ties one OS thread to each incoming request. Threads are expensive — each consumes ~512KB–1MB of stack memory by default. Under heavy load, this forces you to scale horizontally by adding JVM instances rather than handling more concurrency per node. Each JVM brings GC overhead, warm-up cost (JIT compilation), and connection pool pressure on your database.

Project Loom (GA in Java 21) changes this with virtual threads. A single carrier thread can multiplex thousands of virtual threads, blocking I/O no longer parks the OS thread — it parks only the virtual thread. This means a single JVM node can sustain far higher request concurrency before you need another instance.

For horizontal scaling, the shift is significant: you need fewer nodes to handle the same RPS, but each node now needs more heap tuning since virtual threads are cheap to create but objects they hold still pressure GC. Use `-Dspring.threads.virtual.enabled=true` in Spring Boot 3.2+ to opt in with zero code changes.$escape$,
  $escape$import java.util.concurrent.Executors;
import java.net.http.*;
import java.net.URI;

public class VirtualThreadScaling {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        var client = HttpClient.newHttpClient();
        // Platform threads: ~200 concurrent before thread exhaustion
        // Virtual threads: 100,000+ with same memory budget
        try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
            for (int i = 0; i < 10_000; i++) {
                executor.submit(() -> {
                    var req = HttpRequest.newBuilder(URI.create("https://api.example.com/data")).build();
                    client.send(req, HttpResponse.BodyHandlers.ofString()); // blocking I/O is fine here
                });
            }
        }
    }
}$escape$,
  $escape$java$escape$,
